{{inline|date=July 2018}}
'''Egotheism''' is [[Apotheosis|deification]] of the [[self]], or the view that the idea of God is nothing more than a conception of the self. The latter position presupposes the impossibility of divine [[revelation]]. As such, it is a denial of the validity of [[faith]] and most theistic traditions, except for [[deism]]. [[Satanism]] teaches self-deification. Identification of the self with the [[Divinity|divine]] is a tenet of Hinduism ([[Ātman (Hinduism)|Atman]] as the "true self"). A version of egotheism exists in the [[pagan]] cult of [[Antinous]], where it is known as ''homotheosis''.                                         

==References==
* Peabody, Elizabeth Palmer. ''“Egotheism, the Atheism of To-Day”'' 1858, (reprinted in 1886 in her ''Last Evening with Allston'')

